# Shell & Tool Command Playbook

Derived from analyzing 30 real agent transcripts in this workspace over the last
week (~557 Shell calls, 480 Reads, 406 StrReplaces, 234 Greps, 102 Globs). The
two dominant sources of wasted turns were:

1. **Sandbox escalations** — a command was run without `required_permissions`,
   failed, then re-run with `["full_network"]` or `["all"]`. 13 clear
   escalations in one week; some transcripts hit it 3+ times.
2. **Shelling out instead of using the specialized tool** — 75 cases of
   `find -name`, `cat | head`, `grep -r`, `rg`, `sed -i`, or `echo > file`
   that should have been `Glob`, `Read`, `Grep`, `StrReplace`, or `Write`.

Follow this playbook to avoid both classes.

---

## Rule 1 — Pick `required_permissions` up front, not after failure

The sandbox allows filesystem reads, writes **inside the current workspace
root only**, and network only to a small allowlist. Decide permissions from
the command itself, not from retrying after it fails.

### Decision table

| Command shape | Required permissions |
|---|---|
| Read-only shell in workspace (`ls`, `cat`, `git status`, `git log`, `git diff`, `git show` on already-fetched refs) | *(none)* |
| `git fetch`, `git pull`, `git push`, `gh …` (any network) | `["full_network"]` |
| `git worktree add …` (writes to a sibling path outside workspace) | `["all"]` |
| `git commit` / `git rebase` inside a worktree path **outside the current workspace root** | `["all"]` |
| `./gradlew …` (Gradle daemon opens sockets and writes to `~/.gradle`) | `["all"]` |
| `adb install` / `adb uninstall` / any `adb` with `-s <device>` | `["all"]` |
| `python3 script.py` that writes outside the workspace | `["all"]` |
| `chmod`, `mkdir -p` outside the workspace | `["all"]` |
| Anything invoking `mise`, `tuist`, `fastlane`, `bundle exec` | `["all"]` |
| `git fetch origin && git worktree add … origin/<branch>` (fetch + write outside workspace) | `["all"]` (covers both) |

> **Shortcut:** if the command touches a path that is **not** under the current
> Cursor workspace root, assume `["all"]`. If it touches the network and nothing
> else, `["full_network"]`. If both, `["all"]` alone is sufficient — `all`
> implies network.

### Examples proven in this workspace

```bash
# Gradle build — ALWAYS ["all"]
cd /Users/ajo130/code/mpe.app.mamba-android && ./gradlew :app:assembleWorldDebug 2>&1

# Worktree add to sibling path — ALWAYS ["all"]
cd /Users/ajo130/code/mpe.foundation.clickstream && \
  git worktree add -b ajo/release-foundation-android-2.32.0 \
    /Users/ajo130/code/mpe.foundation.clickstream--ajo-release-2.32.0 origin/main

# Fetch only, reading stays in workspace — ["full_network"]
git -C /Users/ajo130/code/mpe.app.mamba-android fetch origin

# Operating on a worktree path outside the current workspace — ["all"]
git -C /Users/ajo130/code/mpe.app.mamba-android--ajo-fix-ios-refs-in-ac-docs \
  rebase origin/rdelgu/docs-ac-updates-april-2026

# adb in a worktree install — ["all"]
~/Library/Android/sdk/platform-tools/adb -s <DEVICE> install "<path-to-apk>"
```

### Anti-pattern seen repeatedly

```bash
# FIRST CALL (fails with sandbox error):
cd /Users/ajo130/code/mpe.app.mamba-android && ./gradlew :app:assembleWorldDebug
# SECOND CALL (succeeds, wasted a turn):
cd /Users/ajo130/code/mpe.app.mamba-android && ./gradlew :app:assembleWorldDebug
# required_permissions: ["all"]
```

Just pick `["all"]` from the start for any Gradle command.

